## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA was removed from macOS**. `DSA.Create()` (and all DSA signing/verification) now throws on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy DSA signatures**, you can't simply switch to ECDSA — the existing signatures were made with DSA. Your options:

1. **Platform-guard macOS** — skip DSA verification on macOS or route it to a Windows/Linux service:
   ```csharp
   if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
       throw new PlatformNotSupportedException(
           "DSA signature verification is not supported on macOS with .NET 11+.");

   using var dsa = DSA.Create();
   // ... verify signature
   ```

2. **Use a cross-platform crypto library** — e.g. [BouncyCastle](https://www.nuget.org/packages/BouncyCastle.Cryptography), which provides a managed DSA implementation that works everywhere:
   ```csharp
   // With BouncyCastle (no OS dependency)
   var dsaParams = new DsaPublicKeyParameters(y, new DsaParameters(p, q, g));
   var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
   signer.Init(false, dsaParams);
   signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
   bool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signature);
   ```

3. **Offload verification** — if signatures are only verified during migration/import, run that workload on Linux or Windows where DSA still works.

**Recommendation:** If you must keep macOS support and can't drop DSA, go with **BouncyCastle**. For new signatures, migrate to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** going forward.
